  "preFix": {
    "title": "Roast gammon",
    "subtitle": "Boiled then glazed, the Boxing Day staple",
    "excerpt": "A gammon joint simmered in cider for two hours then glazed with honey and mustard and roasted until the coating caramelises. Served hot or cold, it is one of the most useful roasting joints.",
    "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136. Boiled and glazed ham entries.\n\nEliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845). Ham and gammon methods.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Gammon is cured pork leg sold raw. The two-stage method here first removes excess salt by simmering, then builds a sticky, burnished exterior by glazing in the oven. It is one of the best roasts to make ahead: the simmer can happen two days before, and the glazing takes just 30 minutes on the day.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
